```java
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        return Math.log(n) / Math.log(3) % 1 == 0;
    }
}
```

This solution works by using the property of logarithms that `log(a^b) = b * log(a)`. So, `log(n) / log(3)` will give us the exponent to which 3 must be raised to get `n`. If this exponent is an integer, then `n` is a power of 3.

However, this solution may not be the most efficient for large numbers because it involves floating point arithmetic. A more efficient solution would be to use a while loop to repeatedly divide `n` by 3 and check if the result is 1. If it is, then `n` is a power of 3.

Here is the while loop solution:

```java
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n /= 3;
        }
        return n == 1;
    }
}
```

This solution has a time complexity of O(log n) and a space complexity of O(1), making it more efficient for large numbers.

